  "prompt": "How does stereo differ from mono?",
  "response": "Stereo and mono differ in how sound is recorded and played back:\n\nMono (Monophonic):\n- Uses a single audio channel\n- Sound comes from one source/speaker\n- All listeners hear identical sound\n- Less spatial depth\n- Simpler recording and playback\n- Typically used in older recordings and basic sound systems\n\nStereo (Stereophonic):\n- Uses two audio channels (left and right)\n- Creates a sense of sound directionality and depth\n- Different sounds can be heard from different speakers\n- Provides a more immersive listening experience\n- Mimics how human ears naturally perceive sound\n- Commonly used in modern music, movies, and sound systems\n\nThe key difference is that stereo provides a more three-dimensional and realistic sound experience by simulating directional audio, while mono offers a single, flat sound source.",
